    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1973-01-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1973-01-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="11"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d11">
                <head>11. Memorandum From Secretary of Defense <persName corresp="#p_LMR_1"
                        >Laird</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d11fn1">Source: National Archives, Nixon
                        Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 888,
                            <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss>, SALT TWO–I–(Geneva), November
                        21, 1972–March 1973. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1973-01-12">January 12, 1973</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Establishment of Standing Consultative Commission (<gloss
                            target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss>)</item>
                </list>
                <p>The Standing Consultative Commission was established on 21 December 1972 with the
                    signing in Geneva of a Memorandum of Understanding.<note n="2" xml:id="d11fn2"
                        >The text of the <gloss target="#t_MOU_1">MOU</gloss> is printed in the
                        Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, January 15, 1973, p.
                        60–61.</note> I believe we should move quickly to appoint the <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> contingent to this <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                        >US</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss> commission for the
                    following reasons.</p>
                <p>—Quick <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> compliance with the Memorandum of
                    Understanding would have maximum political impact on the <gloss
                        target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss>, demonstrating <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                        >US</gloss>
                    <pb facs="0068" n="39" xml:id="pg_39"/> determination to implement the
                    provisions of the <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss> Treaty and Interim
                    Agreement.</p>
                <p>—Immediate establishment of the <gloss target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss> could
                    provide an early recognition of compliance and implementation problems that must
                    be avoided in future <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> agreements.</p>
                <p>—There already are issues of procedures for compliance (e.g., the need for
                    “mutually agreed” procedures for dismantling and destruction of <gloss
                        target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_RandD_1">R&amp;D</gloss> launchers in excess of the number
                    permitted in the treaty) which need attention.</p>
                <p>—Sensitive questions may arise at any time which need careful technical and
                    policy consideration before initiating discussions with the Soviets, having to
                    do with perceived Soviet actions which may be in violation of the agreements and
                    the extent to which we might reveal our intelligence capabilities by challenging
                    Soviet actions.</p>
                <p>—Concurrent operation of the <gloss target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss> and the <gloss
                        target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> delegations would give us more flexibility
                    in the forthcoming sessions of <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> in
                    assigning issues for negotiation, to the <gloss target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss> or
                    to the <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> Delegation, as our negotiating
                    strategy and tactics dictate.</p>
                <p>The immediate actions which need to be taken to establish the <gloss
                        target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss> are:</p>
                <p>—Presidential appointment of the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> Commissioner
                    (a State position), and of the Deputy <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>
                    Commissioner (a Defense position).</p>
                <p>—Formation of a staff to support the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>
                    Commissioners (State and Defense assignments).</p>
                <p>Since future success of <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> negotiations could
                    be linked to what happens in the <gloss target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss>, the
                        <gloss target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss> should be established quickly and staff
                    work begun immediately.</p>
                <p>I am prepared to recommend candidates for these positions and initiate staff
                    support.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed corresp="#p_LMR_1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_LMR_1">Melvin R. Laird</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
